Back-to-school:

First, don’t forget to buy lots of onions and garlic! The germs and coughs are coming. Be prepared and stocked up. 

Oh the feelings that are about to come. 

If your children seem emotionally overwhelmed over the littlest things, know that it is 100% normal during change and transitions. 

So take care of yourself first so you have all of the patience to navigate this phase. 

Balanced School lunch Guide:

Leftovers are always a good idea *

-Protein: beans, eggs, chicken, beef, turkey, seeds, tofu, seed butter. 
-Vegetables & fruits : pick different colors to get different nutrients. Switch it up to create exposure. Cucumbers, carrots, sweet peppers, broccoli, celery, all the berries, grapes cut in half, melons, you name it. 
-Complex carbs: rice, crackers, bread, quino, pasta. 
-Healthy fat: avocado, oil, sunflower butter, seeds, full-fat dairy. 
-Fun snack: bars, dates, muffins, pretzels, chocolate

Labor Day protein balls to satisfy cravings:

1 Cup medjool dates (pitted) 
2/3 Cup gluten free rolled oats
1 Tsp chia seeds
1 Tsp hemp seeds
1/4 Cup cacao nibs
3 Tbsps nut butter. I did sunflower butter because my kids school is nut free. 

➡️In a separate bowl, soak medjool dates in filtered water for about 5 minutes to soften them up
➡️Add all ingredients to blender. Pulse until combined. You want there to be consistency so only blend for a about 1 minute. Pause, check and then blend until necessary.
➡️Roll into desired size balls with your hands. I rolled them into medium sized balls making 10 balls total. Adjust as needed.
➡️Place in the fridge to set for about 10 minutes.
➡️They will last in the refrigerator in a container for about 1 week. Place them in the freezer for longer.

Gluten Free Pumpkin Sheet Pan Pancakes

It’s pumpkin season 🎃 

These are so incredibly easy to make. 

Especially for those days when you are so busy with work. 

They are good for breakfast, for snack, and even for dinner. 

It’ll keep you feeling satisfied for a long time as well. 

2 Cups milk of choice 
1/3 Cup maple syrup
1 Cup pumpkin purée
1 Tsp vanilla extract 
2 Cups GF all purpose flour
1/2 Cup almond flour 
2 tbsps baking baking powder
1/2 Tsp baking soda
1 teaspoon cinnamon or more 

Preheat oven at 350
Mix in all together until smooth. Whisk if you have chunky parts. 
Grease baking sheet 
Bake for 20 minutes 
Allow to cool
🎃Top with maple syrup or nut butter for even more protein. 

It’ll last you for 5 days in the fridge. That’s a lot of meals.

Preheat oven at 375
1 garlic clove
1 1/2 Cup artichoke canned, drained 
In a small food processor, coarsely chop the garlic and artichoke. 
Then in a medium bowl mix with -
1 1/4 spinach thawed and squeezed 
1/2 cup mayo @chosenfoods 
1/2 cup yogurt @siggisdairy (Greek yogurt is another option)
2/3 cup Parmesan
1/2 Cup mozzarella 
Salt to taste
Mix and place in an oven safe dish. 
Bake for 20 minutes

Easiest cashew milk you’ve ever made. 

Spice up your coffee, tea, smoothie or baked goods with this creamy and perfectly sweet cashew milk. 

1 Cup raw unsalted cashews 
3 1/2 Cups filtered water
2 Tsp maple syrup
1 Tsp vanilla extract 
3 pinches of salt

➡️Soak 1 cup of cashews for 30 minutes
➡️Drain
➡️Add all ingredients to blender
➡️Blend until smooth

Lasts in the refrigerator for 5 days.

Ginger Turmeric Lemon Honey Tea 

For the common cold. I made this for my 5 year old that has a gnarly cough. 

It boosts your immune system, helps fight infection, gives you a cough relief, and increases digestion. 

I used Manuka honey - which is known for its antibacterial, antibiotic, and anti-inflammatory properties. 

2 Cups filtered boiled water
1 Tbsp ginger, grated

➡️Boil water
➡️While water is boiling, place all ingredients in a cup

➡️Mix
➡️Let it steep for 5 minutes
Enjoy 🍋

Healthy Tofu Teriyaki Recipe

A tofu recipe that your whole family will love that has 15g of protein per serving. 

Mondays at our house is usually meatless Monday, so this tofu is always on the menu. 

It pairs well with any grain and vegetables. I had lots of sweet potatoes and zucchini to cook so that is what I paired it with. 

1 block extra form tofu, rinsed and drained (@wildwoodfoods has my favorite organic sprouted high protein tofu)
2 tbsps teriyaki sauce or more if needed
2 tbsp tamari sauce 
1 Tsp minced garlic
1 Tsp grated ginger
1 tbsp sesame oil

➡️Cut tofu into small squares
➡️Either whisk together teriyaki, tamari garlic and ginger together before or place and mix over directly on tofu. 
➡️Heat sesame oil over medium pan or wok 
➡️Spread tofu evenly and flip halfway through. 20 minutes or until tofu starts to roast and turn golden brown

Healthy butternut squash soup 

This soup is incredibly nourishing and versatile. Keep it simple with just butternut squash or add sweet potatoes and/or carrots. 

1 medium butternut squash 
*Option - add 2-3 medium sweet potatoes or carrots
1 yellow onion
3 garlic cloves 
4 cups filtered water 
1/2 tsp salt or more according to taste
2 tbsp extra virgin olive oil
1 Tblsp rosemary - add fresh for even more flavor 

➡️Peel and chop squash, onion and garlic
➡️Sauté onions over medium heat with EVOO & salt for 5 minutes or until translucent
➡️Add garlic and butternut squash (add sweet potatoes and/or carrots) for about 10 minutes when squash starts to soften up 
➡️Add water and rosemary 
➡️Boil
➡️Cover and simmer for 25 minutes
➡️Blend with handheld blender or let it cool and transfer to blender

Sync your exercise routine with your menstrual cycle:

➡️To reconnect with your body
➡️To match your energy & hormone fluctuations 
➡️Burn more fat
➡️Build more muscle

✨Menstrual phase (days 0-7): walking, stretching & even sleeping is a sport during this phase. 
✨Follicular phase (days 8-13): HIIT, cardio activities and heavy weight strength training. 
✨Ovulation phase (days 14-17): high intensity and endurance workouts such as running, CrossFit, cycling, etc. 
✨Luteal phase (days 17- menstruation): low-intensity workouts like yoga, Pilates, strength training, hikes. 

Always listen to your body.

I vividly remember sitting at the dining room table, time and time again, as a little girl being told I couldn’t get up from the table until I was done with my plate. Especially with my veggies. I would cry or throw it up. 

Just last night I had a conversation with someone about how they were forced to eat veggies as a kid too. Ever since she started the method of eating them raw before meals, she found herself to actually love their taste and has less mental chatter about food. 

Unlearning takes time. Acknowledging is the first step. Second is to get to know yourself again. Start to play with different vegetables, colors and textures. Try them raw. Try them cooked (baked, air-fry) or mix them in smoothies since you can’t taste them.
